    "Milton P. Horne": "); the closing statement concerns the inability to\nfind wisdom (\nv. 1\nand\nv. 1, p\u2211\u00a1er, occurs here in\n[v_Dan_2_4] Hebrew and in Aramaic in Daniel 2:4, 5, 6, 7, 9, 16, 24, and in\nQumran literature. Clearly, it is late terminology. However, its\n[v_Gen_40_5] cognate, pitr\u00f4n, occurs in Genesis 40:5 and 8, in the narrative\ncontext where one wise individual offers a king an interpretation.\nIn the context of Genesis 40, Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]` is a wise man who knew the\n\u201cinterpretation,\u201d pitr\u00f4n, of a dream. Whether the sage here intends\nthe allusion to the Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]` story is not clear, but the allusiveness of\nthe opening rhetorical question forms a provocative connection to\nthe ensuing concern on the whims of a king.\nThe observation in\nV. 1 Can anyone know wisdom?\nVv. 2-4 The power of a king",
    "Terence E. Fretheim, Thomas B. Slater": "8\n336",
